Top Stories (January 11)

WASHINGTON CALIFORNIA POWER TALKS HUNG UP ON FORWARD-CONTRACT TERMS
White House-brokered talks to resolve California's electricity crisis were 
hung up Wednesday on the terms of long-term power deals being negotiated 
between the state's two largest utilities and generators, persons close to 
the talks said.
http://199.97.97.79/IMDS%PMADJN0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/djn/2001/
01/11/eng-djn/eng-djn_010028_105_512227392755

OFFICIALS LOOK TO WHOLESALE POWER SUPPLIERS FOR HELP IN ENERGY CRISIS
Representatives of the Clinton administration, California Gov. Gray Davis' 
office and California's biggest power companies continued to work yesterday 
to solve the state's electricity crisis.
http://199.97.97.163/IMDS%PMAKRT0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/knightri
dder/2001/01/11/krtbn/0000-0481-WT-ENERGY-CRISIS

TEXAS ELECTRIC UTILITIES SAY STATE ON TRACK WITH DEREGULATION
An association of Texas' largest electric utilities remains committed to the 
state's plan to inject competition into Texas' $19 billion a year retail 
power market.
http://199.97.97.79/IMDS%PMADJN0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/djn/2001/
01/11/eng-djn/eng-djn_140034_79_039338498842

PACIFICORP TO BUY, SELL WIND FARM ELECTRICITY
PacifiCorp announced Wednesday that it has agreed to purchase all the output 
of a 450-turbine wind farm to be built southwest of Walla Walla straddling 
the Oregon-Washington border.
http://199.97.97.163/IMDS%PMANAT0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/tricityh
erald/2001/01/11/eng-tricity_news/eng-tricity_news_061310_70_6640397640876

BRITISH ENERGY REGULATOR SEEKS TO IMPOSE CONDITIONS ON ELECTRICITY GENERATORS
Energy regulator Ofgem is considering introducing a market abuse condition 
into electricity generators' licences just weeks after the Competition 
Commission threw out a similar clause.
http://199.97.97.163/IMDS%PMAKRT0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/knightri
dder/2001/01/11/krtbn/0000-0393-SU-ELECTRIC

